            'description' => '<p><b>Aristippus of Cyrene</b> (<span></span>; Greek: <span lang="grc" title="Ancient Greek language text">Ἀρίστιππος ὁ Κυρηναῖος</span>; c. 435 – c. 356 BCE) was the founder of the Cyrenaic school of Philosophy. He was a pupil of Socrates, but adopted a very different philosophical outlook, teaching that the goal of life was to seek pleasure by circumstances to oneself and by maintaining proper control over both adversity and prosperity. His outlook came to be called "ethical hedonism." Among his pupils was his daughter Arete.
</p><p>There are indications that he was conflated with his grandson, Aristippus the Younger.</p>',
