            'description' => '<p><b>Marsilius of Padua</b> (Italian: <i>Marsilio</i> or <i>Marsiglio da Padova</i>; born <i>Marsilio dei Mainardini</i> or <i>Marsilio Mainardini</i>; c. 1275 – c. 1342) was an Italian scholar, trained in medicine,  who practiced a variety of professions. He was also an important 14th-century political figure. His political treatise <i>Defensor pacis</i> (The Defender of Peace), an attempt to refute papalist claims to a "plenitude of power" in affairs of both church and state, is seen by some authorities as the most revolutionary political treatise written in the later Middle Ages. It is one of the first examples of a reasoned defense of caesaropapism in Western Europe.</p>',
