            'description' => '<p><b>Jean Buridan</b> (<small>French: </small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[byʁidɑ̃]</span>; Latin: <i>Johannes Buridanus</i>; <abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span> 1300</span> – c.<span> 1358/61</span>) was an influential 14th century French philosopher.
</p><p>Buridan was a teacher in the faculty of arts at the University of Paris for his entire career, focusing in particular on logic and the works of Aristotle. Buridan sowed the seeds of the Copernican revolution in Europe. He developed the concept of impetus, the first step toward the modern concept of inertia and an important development in the history of medieval science. His name is most familiar through the thought experiment known as Buridan\'s ass, however this thought experiment does not appear in his extant writings.
</p>',
