                'description' => '<p><b>José Ortega y Gasset</b> (<small>Spanish: </small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[xoˈse orˈteɣa i ɣaˈset]</span>; 9 May 1883 – 18 October 1955) was a Spanish philosopher, and essayist. He worked during the first half of the 20th century, while Spain oscillated between monarchy, republicanism, and dictatorship. His philosophy has been characterized as a "philosophy of life" that "comprised a long-hidden beginning in a pragmatist metaphysics inspired by William James, and with a general method from a realist phenomenology imitating Edmund Husserl, which served both his proto-existentialism (prior to Martin Heidegger\'s) and his realist historicism, which has been compared to both Wilhelm Dilthey and Benedetto Croce."</p>',
