                    'stored_json_file' => NULL,
                'description' => '<p><b>Gilles Deleuze</b> (<small>French: </small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)">[ʒil dəløz]</span>; 18 January 1925 – 4 November 1995) was a French philosopher who, from the early 1960s until his death in 1995, wrote on philosophy, literature, film, and fine art. His most popular works were the two volumes of <i>Capitalism and Schizophrenia</i>: <i>Anti-Oedipus</i> (1972) and <i>A Thousand Plateaus</i> (1980), both co-written with psychoanalyst Félix Guattari.  His metaphysical treatise <i>Difference and Repetition</i> (1968) is considered by many scholars to be his magnum opus. A. W. Moore, citing Bernard Williams\'s criteria for a great thinker, ranks Deleuze among the "greatest philosophers". His work has influenced a variety of disciplines across philosophy and art, including literary theory, post-structuralism and postmodernism.</p>',
