                'description' => '<p><b>Shang Yang</b> (<span></span>; Chinese: <span lang="zh-Hant">商鞅</span>; pinyin: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-pinyin">Shāng Yāng</span></i>), or <b>Wei Yang</b> (Chinese: <span lang="zh">衞鞅</span>; pinyin: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-pinyin">Wèi Yāng</span></i>; born with the surname <b>Gongsun</b> in Wey, Zhou Kingdom; c. 390 – 338 BCE), was a statesman and reformer of the State of Qin during the Warring States period of ancient China. His policies laid the foundation that enabled Qin to conquer all of China, uniting the country for the first time and ushering in the Qin dynasty. He and his followers contributed to the Book of Lord Shang strain of what has modernly been termed Chinese Legalism.</p>',
