                    'description' => '<p>
<b>Ānandavardhana</b> (820–890) was the author of <i>Dhvanyāloka</i>, a work articulating the philosophy of "aesthetic suggestion". The philosopher Abhinavagupta wrote an important commentary on it.
</p><p>Ānandavardhana is credited with creating the <i>dhvani</i> theory. He wrote of <i>dhvani</i> (meaning sound, or resonance) in regard to the "soul of poetry." "When the poet writes," said Ānandavardhana, "he creates a resonant field of emotions."  To understand the poetry, the reader or hearer must be on the same "wavelength."  The method requires sensitivity on the parts of the writer and the reader. The complete <i>Dhvanyāloka</i> together with Abhinavagupta\'s commentary on it has been translated into English by the eminent sanskritist Daniel H.H. Ingalls and his collaborators.</p>',
