                    'description' => '<p> 

<b>Gangesha Upadhyaya</b> (Sanskrit: <span lang="sa">गंगेश उपाध्याय</span>, <i>Gaṅgeśa Upādhyāya</i>) (late 12th century) was an Indian mathematician and philosopher from the kingdom of  Mithila. He established the Navya-Nyāya ("New Logic") school. His <i>Tattvacintāmaṇi</i> (The Jewel of Thought on the Nature of  Things), also known as <i>Pramāṇacintāmaṇi</i> (The Jewel of Thought on the Means of Valid Knowledge), is the basic text for all later developments. The logicians of this school were primarily interested in defining their terms and concepts related to non-binary logical categories.
</p>',
