            'description' => '<p><b>Ban Zhao</b> (Chinese: <span lang="zh">班昭</span>; pinyin: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-pinyin"><b>Bān Zhāo</b></span></i>; Wade–Giles: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-wadegile"><b>Pan<sup>1</sup> Chao<sup>1</sup></b></span></i>; 45 – c. 116 CE), courtesy name <b>Huiban</b> (Chinese: <span lang="zh">惠班</span>; pinyin: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-pinyin"><b>Huìbān</b></span></i>; Wade–Giles: <i><span lang="zh-Latn-wadegile"><b>Hui<sup>4</sup>-Pan<sup>1</sup></b></span></i>), was a Chinese historian, philosopher, and politician. She was the first known female Chinese historian. She completed her brother Ban Gu\'s work on the history of the Western Han, the <i>Book of Han</i>. She also wrote <i>Lessons for Women</i>, an influential work on women\'s conduct. She also had great interest in astronomy and mathematics and wrote poems, commemorative writings, argumentations, commentaries, essays and several longer works, not all of which survive. She became China\'s most famous female scholar and an instructor of Taoist sexual practices for the imperial family.</p>',
